  <li id='source-emissions-from-peat-drainage' class='source-item'>
    <div class='source_header'>
      <strong class='source_title'>Emissions from Peat Drainage</strong>
    </div>

    <div class='source_body'>
      <div class='source_summary'>
        <p>Development of agriculture and other human activities on peatlands requires drainage, which leads to
        increased CO2 emissions to the atmosphere from peat decomposition. Highly productive croplands, including plantations, will always be 100% drained (Hooijer et al. 2010).</p>
        <p>Here, we apply a Tier 1 methodology (IPCC 2014) to estimate annual CO2 emissions from peat drainage based on the area of overlap between mapped areas of large industrial plantations in 2013/2014 (Transparent World 2015) and mapped areas of peatlands (Indonesian Ministry of Agriculture 2011), and apply an emission factor of 15 t CO2 ha-1 yr-1, based on guidance provided in Equation 2.3 and Table 2.1 of IPCC (2014).</p>

        <p class='credits'><strong>Citations:</strong> Hooijer, A., Page, S., Canadell, J.G., Silvius, M., Kwadijk, J., Wosten, H.W. and Jauhiainen, J. 2010. Current and future CO2 emissions from drained peatlands in Southeast Asia. Biogeosciences 7, 1505-1514.</p>
        <p class="credits">IPCC 2014, 2013 Supplement to the 2006 IPCC Guidelines for National Greenhouse Gas Inventories: Wetlands, Hiraishi, T., Krug, T., Tanabe, K., Srivastava, N., Baasansuren, J., Fukuda, M. and Troxler, T.G. (eds). Published: IPCC, Switzerland.</p>
        <p class="credits">Transparent World. “Tree Plantations.” 2015. Data available on Global Forest Watch. <a href="http://www.globalforestwatch.org" target="_blank">www.globalforestwatch.org</a></p>
        <p class="credits">Peatlands map, Indonesian Ministry of Agriculture, 2011. Prepared by World Resources Institute (2015).</p>


      </div>
